WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:14.880
Hi, I'm Vicki Boykis. I'm a machine learning engineer at Automatic, the company behind WordPress.com.

00:00:14.880 --> 00:00:20.320
But today I don't want to talk about machine learning or data. What I do want to talk about

00:00:20.320 --> 00:00:25.840
is building a digital garden. And I want to explain why this is important by talking a

00:00:25.840 --> 00:00:31.600
little bit about what my daily routine looks like in the longest year of our lives in 2020.

00:00:31.600 --> 00:00:36.080
And I'm hoping that as a data scientist, it extrapolates and generalizes to what

00:00:36.080 --> 00:00:42.639
everybody's environment looks like and what we can do about some of that. So my day usually starts

00:00:42.639 --> 00:00:49.279
around three o'clock in the morning. That's when my youngest son wakes up. He's very little. So I

00:00:49.279 --> 00:00:55.040
usually have to put him back to bed and wait on him to settle down. And while I'm doing that,

00:00:55.040 --> 00:00:59.680
I do my favorite activity, which is doom scrolling through Twitter. Nothing's really

00:00:59.680 --> 00:01:06.800
changed on Twitter since the last time I read it, maybe three, four hours ago. But it always

00:01:06.800 --> 00:01:12.559
makes me feel worse coming away from it than I do going into it. And so I'm filled with this

00:01:12.559 --> 00:01:20.639
endless anxiety of news items that have happened. So then he settles back down. I go back to sleep.

00:01:20.639 --> 00:01:25.040
But in the meantime, I'm woken up around four o'clock in the morning by a text message from

00:01:25.040 --> 00:01:31.519
my state, which is an alert to be careful of COVID, for the hospital restrictions to keep

00:01:31.519 --> 00:01:37.599
masking and to be aware that the rates in our area are on the rise. This is kind of helpful

00:01:37.599 --> 00:01:43.680
information, but not really because it also makes me feel more anxious than relieved. And it brings

00:01:43.680 --> 00:01:49.360
me more questions than answers, really. For example, when's the next time I'll get to see

00:01:49.360 --> 00:01:55.919
my elderly relatives? Will schools stay open for the next couple weeks or so? How are we doing as

00:01:55.919 --> 00:02:01.599
a country? And when will it get better? And of course, none of us can answer that. So I'm left

00:02:01.599 --> 00:02:08.399
feeling even more anxious. Of course, by the time all that's over, I go to the numbers. I look at

00:02:08.399 --> 00:02:14.160
the COVID tracking project, which is a really wonderful project put together by a group that

00:02:14.240 --> 00:02:19.360
tracks totals across each state. Although it doesn't make me feel any better either, even

00:02:19.360 --> 00:02:25.440
though there's very good information because the COVID rates are on the rise, it's exponential,

00:02:25.440 --> 00:02:31.520
and it doesn't seem to be ending anytime soon. So by the time that's all over, it's usually around

00:02:31.520 --> 00:02:37.679
seven o'clock in the morning, which is when my older child, my daughter, wakes up. And she also

00:02:37.679 --> 00:02:44.000
has a lot of pings and needs. Usually hers are more like, what hippopotamuses eat? And what are

00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:49.119
the phases of the moon? So I help her get ready and get dressed, and then we go downstairs to

00:02:49.119 --> 00:02:56.720
breakfast. Breakfast, I use the term very loosely because as a family with small kids, it's just

00:02:56.720 --> 00:03:02.960
pretty much chaos. So during that time, I get some time to catch up on what's been going on at work.

00:03:03.520 --> 00:03:09.600
I usually don't have 99 Slack notifications, but since we do work in a distributed, remote,

00:03:09.600 --> 00:03:14.320
and asynchronous way, there's usually someone working all around the world, even when I'm

00:03:14.320 --> 00:03:21.199
asleep. So there's definitely writing and reading to catch up on. So when that's all over, I go to

00:03:21.919 --> 00:03:26.800
my favorite part of Twitter to catch up on, which is data Twitter. And it seems like overnight,

00:03:26.800 --> 00:03:32.080
there have been five million more data analyses published, 10 million more new deep learning

00:03:32.080 --> 00:03:38.800
frameworks, and 15 million more data controversies. And it's a lot to keep up with, and I feel like I

00:03:38.800 --> 00:03:45.600
never can. So it all adds to the compounding anxiety of the things that I have to keep up with

00:03:45.600 --> 00:03:52.800
in 2020. So after being pinged all morning and exposed to the stressful world of 2020 during

00:03:52.800 --> 00:03:58.320
COVID and the amplification of that world in my digital media, I start hearing not the individual

00:03:58.320 --> 00:04:05.520
noise, but the steady stream of Radio KFKD. Radio KFKD is a concept Anne Lamott talks about in her

00:04:05.520 --> 00:04:10.960
wonderful book about the creative process, Bird by Bird. Lamott says that KFKD plays for all creative

00:04:10.960 --> 00:04:15.520
people. She says there's two speakers. The left is the noise that you hear when you think you're

00:04:15.520 --> 00:04:20.079
better than everybody else, and the right is the noise when you think you're worse than everybody

00:04:20.079 --> 00:04:25.519
else. And I count data professionals, data professionals, within creative people too,

00:04:25.519 --> 00:04:32.959
because we have a lot of technical work that we have to do, and a lot of very judgmental-based

00:04:32.959 --> 00:04:41.279
work that is more of an art form than a science. Today we're living in Radio KFKD, but over top of

00:04:41.279 --> 00:04:47.200
that is the pandemic. So it's what I like to call Radio 2020. The right speaker is everything we've

00:04:47.200 --> 00:04:52.399
mentioned. The noise of other people's perfection on social media, the noise of controversy, of

00:04:52.399 --> 00:04:58.079
amplified fears, of heighten everything, a platform that is constantly on, and a black mirror that

00:04:58.079 --> 00:05:03.679
reflects our worst fears and beliefs. The left speaker is all the news we're constantly processing

00:05:03.679 --> 00:05:10.559
about living in uncertain times, and over top of all that is the never-ending static of the pandemic

00:05:10.559 --> 00:05:17.200
that won't end. Fears for us and our loved ones, constant restrictions, and when we need it the

00:05:17.200 --> 00:05:23.359
most, isolation. Being isolated is hard enough as a human. Being isolated and bombarded by the

00:05:23.359 --> 00:05:29.040
radio of 2020, the noise of clickbait doomscrolling, constantly being surrounded by information that

00:05:29.040 --> 00:05:35.200
is largely negative is impossible. So what can we do about all of this? Well, we can't really change

00:05:35.200 --> 00:05:40.239
our physical space. We can't change the state of the world right now. We can't change the people

00:05:40.239 --> 00:05:46.720
that rely on us. We can't change the human interactions that we have. What we can change

00:05:46.720 --> 00:05:52.720
is the digital world that we operate in. And so I want to talk a little bit about what the aspect of

00:05:52.720 --> 00:06:00.320
that digital world are, and how we can change it. Why is radio 2020 so good at derailing us?

00:06:01.119 --> 00:06:07.600
And why is it constantly creating noise for us? There's three reasons. First of all is that online

00:06:07.600 --> 00:06:14.799
it's noisy, and this has been the case since even before 2020. In a conference that I attended and

00:06:14.799 --> 00:06:20.959
spoke at, Skeptak, several years ago, one of the speakers that really stood out to me was Natasha

00:06:21.040 --> 00:06:28.239
Daushul, who is a sociologist and professor at New York University. And she wrote a book called

00:06:28.239 --> 00:06:34.880
Addicted by Design that was talking about all the different ways that our online universes today

00:06:35.440 --> 00:06:42.799
are a lot like casinos. The summary of her research is that much of the online world,

00:06:42.799 --> 00:06:48.480
particularly social media companies, much like casinos, are designed to draw our attention away

00:06:48.480 --> 00:06:54.160
in small bursts. As a result, to get our attention and retain you on the platform,

00:06:54.720 --> 00:07:00.480
sites often do things like send you a combination of mobile alerts, notifications, and emails.

00:07:01.279 --> 00:07:06.399
Sometimes this engagement is good, like if we're discovering interesting blog posts, or donating

00:07:06.399 --> 00:07:13.519
to creators, or watching original content. But oftentimes it can simply be noise. The online

00:07:13.519 --> 00:07:18.480
noise interferes with our ability to concentrate on longer-term projects and engage in longer-term

00:07:18.480 --> 00:07:24.320
thinking. And the problem is that there's always new noise and always new content online.

00:07:26.640 --> 00:07:30.640
A second problem with this content is a lot of it is very superlative.

00:07:31.279 --> 00:07:37.679
What do I mean when I say superlative? Usually you only get the very worst or the very best,

00:07:37.679 --> 00:07:41.279
because that's what actually filters through the noise and creates engagement.

00:07:42.079 --> 00:07:49.519
So as an example, if someone is posting their pictures of vacation online, although not recently

00:07:49.519 --> 00:07:56.079
these days, but if they are, you'll usually only see the best pictures for their hotel room. You

00:07:56.079 --> 00:08:03.119
won't actually see how they were late for their flight, or had problems at the airport, or had

00:08:03.119 --> 00:08:08.000
transportation issues. You only get the highlights. And the same is true with all the worst news

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:13.600
stories of 2020 especially, because those are the ones that are optimized to get us to click.

00:08:13.600 --> 00:08:19.119
So we'll only see the very very worst, and we won't see what's progressing more in the median

00:08:19.119 --> 00:08:25.279
and in the long term. The third problem is that online is worse in the context of the current

00:08:25.279 --> 00:08:30.160
state of the internet. The enormous amount of additional pressure 2020 has put on both of our

00:08:30.160 --> 00:08:38.080
physical and digital lives has pulled us apart as humans, which means that we can't meet with anybody

00:08:38.799 --> 00:08:43.599
and we're left to face the crisis in the context of the current state of the internet on our own.

00:08:46.479 --> 00:08:52.320
So we have this crisis that's occurring both in the physical world, with everything that's

00:08:52.320 --> 00:08:57.679
been happening during the pandemic, and in the digital world with a crisis for our attention as well.

00:08:58.640 --> 00:09:05.119
How do we fight this? One of the best ways that I found personally is to be able to control it

00:09:05.679 --> 00:09:11.919
a very small bit of the time, and the best way to do that is to build your own digital garden.

00:09:15.039 --> 00:09:22.400
Anne Lamott in Bird by Bird says that the best thing to do is to take it piece by piece, and the

00:09:22.400 --> 00:09:28.080
title of the book comes from a book report that her brother had to write. 30 years ago, she writes,

00:09:28.080 --> 00:09:33.359
my older brother, who was 10 years old at the time, was trying to get a report on birds that he'd

00:09:33.359 --> 00:09:39.840
written that he had three months to write. It was due the next day. We were out at our family cabin

00:09:39.840 --> 00:09:45.520
in Bolinas, and he was in the kitchen table, close to tears, surrounded by binder, paper, and pencils,

00:09:45.520 --> 00:09:52.000
and opened up books by birds, immobilized by the task at hand. Then my father sat down beside him,

00:09:52.080 --> 00:09:56.960
put his arm around my brother's shoulder, and said, bird by bird, buddy, just take it bird by bird.

00:09:58.080 --> 00:10:03.919
The idea is that we can't change everything, but even changing a little tiny bit of our environment

00:10:03.919 --> 00:10:09.599
is better than changing nothing. So what's a way that you can fix the world and change it

00:10:09.599 --> 00:10:14.960
bird by bird? The best way to do that is by planting a garden. The Secret Garden is a book

00:10:14.960 --> 00:10:20.799
by Frances Hogson Burnett, who lived in America and England in the 19th century. The story is

00:10:20.799 --> 00:10:27.039
about a girl named Mary, whose parents died in a cholera epidemic in colonial India. It's kind

00:10:27.039 --> 00:10:32.320
of sad, but her parents never saw her much anyway. She was cared for by servants, and as a result,

00:10:32.320 --> 00:10:37.679
she had grown spoiled, selfish, and extremely lonely. She sent to England to her uncle's estate

00:10:37.679 --> 00:10:45.200
on the Moors. The Moors are a beautiful, lonely, and foreboding place. And just like the Moors,

00:10:45.200 --> 00:10:50.080
the house where Mary stays is dark and cold, as is often the case in British literature,

00:10:50.080 --> 00:10:55.679
full of secrets. It's revealed that Mary's aunt, who died, had a secret garden in the house that

00:10:55.679 --> 00:11:01.679
was then locked up. When Mary comes to the garden, it's neglected. She begins to tend to it, and in

00:11:01.679 --> 00:11:07.119
the process of caring for it and watching things grow, she forgets to feel sorry for herself and

00:11:07.119 --> 00:11:13.679
her parents. The process of caring for it brings her back to life. So right now, we're all a little

00:11:13.760 --> 00:11:19.919
bit like Mary, at the start of a garden that's fallow. We're lost. We're not quite sure what to

00:11:19.919 --> 00:11:26.080
do. So there's some things that we can do, and next I want to talk about things that people have done,

00:11:26.719 --> 00:11:31.280
and then end with some suggestions for maybe smaller things that you can do to get started.

00:11:33.200 --> 00:11:37.440
So how do we fix this? How do we create something that's for our public garden

00:11:38.080 --> 00:11:42.880
and makes the internet better at the same time? I'll talk about a couple of different ways that

00:11:42.880 --> 00:11:47.280
people in the community have done this, and that I've done this, and then offer some more

00:11:47.280 --> 00:11:53.520
lightweight suggestions if these seem overwhelming to you. The first and best way, in my opinion,

00:11:54.159 --> 00:12:00.000
is to write something from your perspective. David Robinson has a really good blog post about this.

00:12:00.000 --> 00:12:06.000
He writes a bunch about statistics in R as well. He said that if you write something, if you tell

00:12:06.000 --> 00:12:11.200
somebody something three times, then you should write a blog about it. And he says that it's

00:12:11.200 --> 00:12:16.960
important to write a blog for a data science career portfolio. And I think it's important not

00:12:16.960 --> 00:12:22.159
just for that, but because it allows you to create something that you're in control of on your own

00:12:22.159 --> 00:12:28.400
platform that doesn't change, and that counteracts the way that social media works, and that you can

00:12:28.400 --> 00:12:34.559
come back to again and again and have it always be the same. You can write about anything from

00:12:35.119 --> 00:12:40.320
analytics, from your opinion on certain trends, certain packages you've done.

00:12:40.880 --> 00:12:45.599
So these topics have been written about hundreds of thousands of times before data analysis

00:12:46.479 --> 00:12:51.280
and tidyverse, but the important thing is that it's coming from your perspective. Everybody

00:12:51.280 --> 00:12:55.599
comes to the story with a completely different perspective, completely different set of life

00:12:55.599 --> 00:12:59.840
skills, and history, and work skills, and the internet wants to hear about them.

00:13:00.479 --> 00:13:06.559
Two really great recent examples of this from our blogger are this recent article about pipes,

00:13:07.760 --> 00:13:12.479
about the pipe tool, and a spoonful of Hugo. How much Hugo do I need to know?

00:13:13.119 --> 00:13:19.280
Neither of these are very long and complex topics, but they break down what you need to know

00:13:19.280 --> 00:13:25.280
in very specific ways, and they're talking about it from the author's experience. So these are

00:13:25.280 --> 00:13:31.280
both fantastic. The way that I've done this is in a couple of different ways. One of the places

00:13:31.280 --> 00:13:39.359
I'm active on is my technical blog, and I write about machine learning, and data, and metrics.

00:13:39.359 --> 00:13:43.760
My main goal on my blog is to write about things that I don't really see anywhere else on the

00:13:43.760 --> 00:13:48.640
blogosphere, or write them from my perspective. And the other thing is that in the process of

00:13:48.640 --> 00:13:54.239
writing more technical posts, you get more insight into what's going on and a better understanding as

00:13:54.239 --> 00:14:01.599
well. So some things I've written about are getting machine learning to production, the Spark

00:14:02.159 --> 00:14:09.919
API using R, and in a very serious examination, breaking down the iOS screen time report.

00:14:09.919 --> 00:14:14.799
None of these are breakthrough topics. In particular, getting machine learning to production

00:14:14.799 --> 00:14:19.760
is a topic that has been covered over and over again. But this is my take on the topic. These

00:14:19.760 --> 00:14:24.559
are things that are interesting and important to me, and now I have them to refer back to in my blog.

00:14:26.080 --> 00:14:31.520
Another place I've been writing is my newsletter, Normcore Tech, where I look at machine learning

00:14:31.520 --> 00:14:36.559
and data, but more from a human-centered perspective. I started again because I didn't

00:14:36.559 --> 00:14:41.919
see anyone covering these topics in quite the same way. Sure, we all talk about Google, and Facebook,

00:14:41.919 --> 00:14:46.159
and social media every week, but there were things that I wanted to understand better.

00:14:46.799 --> 00:14:51.359
Here are some recent things I've talked about. How a lot of the products that we use are built

00:14:51.359 --> 00:14:57.200
by consensus, by an average of 10,000 people in San Francisco, and what impact that has for our

00:14:57.200 --> 00:15:02.239
online world. What happens when the internet stops in a country, as it did in Belarus

00:15:02.239 --> 00:15:06.159
in the middle of 2020, and how the internet actually gets from country to country.

00:15:06.799 --> 00:15:10.799
And how Google Drive, which is ubiquitous in most of the companies I've been at,

00:15:10.799 --> 00:15:15.520
is actually production because we store really sensitive data in there, and when it goes down,

00:15:15.520 --> 00:15:20.320
it can be a problem. Another interesting thing that happens when you write about things that

00:15:20.320 --> 00:15:25.760
are of interest to you is you start getting people who are also drawn to these topics.

00:15:25.760 --> 00:15:30.400
So when I first started my newsletter, I didn't get any emails, but then slowly and surely,

00:15:30.400 --> 00:15:34.400
I got more people talking to me about these topics from their perspective as well.

00:15:34.400 --> 00:15:39.440
So it's a wonderful way for building a community, even if you didn't initially intend it to be.

00:15:40.479 --> 00:15:45.039
The second way, if you want to go a little bit of a more technical route, is to empower people

00:15:45.039 --> 00:15:51.679
to understand data. Data literacy these days is really, really important with how confusing

00:15:51.679 --> 00:15:57.840
and clickbait-oriented the internet has become. And anyone who helps make sense of that data and

00:15:57.840 --> 00:16:03.840
make it trustworthy is a superhero. A fantastic example of this is the work of Julia Szilagyi,

00:16:04.719 --> 00:16:10.320
who has created books, courses, and writes on her own blog about topics like Tidy Tuesday,

00:16:10.320 --> 00:16:17.440
as well as showcases videos. She does a fantastic job of explaining and making it accessible and

00:16:17.440 --> 00:16:24.159
has that content on her site to own. Another wonderful example is the R-Lady Sydney course

00:16:24.159 --> 00:16:29.599
created by Lisa Williams, who was inspired by her own frustrations of getting started with R.

00:16:29.599 --> 00:16:35.440
The course goes through getting started, packaging, and R markdown, and it's another great way to

00:16:35.440 --> 00:16:39.200
work through what you're interested in, as well as share it with other people.

00:16:40.320 --> 00:16:44.880
Another person who has done a wonderful job empowering people from the Python community this

00:16:44.880 --> 00:16:50.799
time is Ines Montagny, who works in the natural language processing space on the Python package

00:16:50.799 --> 00:16:55.359
Spacey. And not only does she have clear explanations how to use the package, she

00:16:55.359 --> 00:17:00.320
open-sourced a whole library that allows you to create your own course.

00:17:00.479 --> 00:17:05.599
Finally, cultivating your own garden can simply be about being human and creating connections.

00:17:06.400 --> 00:17:11.680
One of my favorite examples about this is the illustrative work of Alison Horst,

00:17:11.680 --> 00:17:16.160
who creates illustrations both for her own talks and for use in the R community.

00:17:16.719 --> 00:17:21.920
And they're just beautiful, they're fun, they're interesting, and they're creative ways to think

00:17:21.920 --> 00:17:28.000
about a topic that hasn't really been covered in the same way before. One of the recordings

00:17:28.880 --> 00:17:33.359
One of the recurring themes of Norm Core Tech, my newsletter, has been that even though we all sit

00:17:33.359 --> 00:17:39.119
in machines and write code or munch data for a great deal of the day, we ultimately crave human

00:17:39.119 --> 00:17:43.839
connection, as we do during this pandemic and isolation. We don't have a way to hand off

00:17:43.839 --> 00:17:49.359
physical things, especially now. Cultivating our own garden that's not subject to the radio

00:17:49.359 --> 00:17:57.119
frequencies of radio KFKD is a wonderful way to do that. But what if you're overwhelmed by

00:17:58.079 --> 00:18:00.400
the idea of getting started and don't know how?

00:18:03.040 --> 00:18:08.560
There's a lot of really small ideas that you can draw from as well, that don't necessarily involve

00:18:08.560 --> 00:18:14.800
creating a course or making videos or creating your own blog. And so I want to cover some of

00:18:14.800 --> 00:18:19.439
those things as well. If you're feeling intimidated by these very large scale,

00:18:19.439 --> 00:18:25.359
broad ranging projects, there's much smaller ways to get started. And in fact, one of the

00:18:25.359 --> 00:18:31.599
ways that I got started was by creating a blog and drawing memes, something like 10 years ago.

00:18:31.599 --> 00:18:36.239
And I've been hooked on content creation ever since. So there's some much smaller ways that

00:18:36.239 --> 00:18:42.000
you can approach things. One of the first things you can do is just make a commitment to write

00:18:42.000 --> 00:18:49.040
200 words once a month. The most important thing is that you're writing in a space that you feel

00:18:49.040 --> 00:18:53.920
comfortable writing and that is not an impediment. As an employee of Automatic, I can recommend

00:18:53.920 --> 00:18:59.599
WordPress.com. But it doesn't really have to be that. Just any place where the technology is not

00:18:59.599 --> 00:19:06.479
impeding you for making small progress on a bunch of words every day. The second thing that you can

00:19:06.479 --> 00:19:14.079
do is share a piece of code. If the idea of blogging seems overwhelming, sharing code and

00:19:14.079 --> 00:19:18.400
talking about code can be a stepping stone to cultivating an online place of your own.

00:19:19.119 --> 00:19:26.479
It's extremely easy to write markdown posts in GitHub. And as an added bonus is learning an

00:19:26.479 --> 00:19:31.920
industry tool that's very widely used. Something that I started that I copied from Simon Willison

00:19:31.920 --> 00:19:36.959
is a directory called TIL, today I learned, full of random code snippets and pieces.

00:19:36.959 --> 00:19:42.239
The benefit of this is that you come back to it again and again. I know that's true for me. And

00:19:42.239 --> 00:19:47.040
you won't lose it. And you have it for others to share as well. In a world of incomplete stack

00:19:47.040 --> 00:19:51.680
overflow answers, think of this as your stack overflow that's filled with your specific

00:19:51.680 --> 00:19:57.920
questions and answers for your needs. You can also make a comic. It might not seem like it,

00:19:57.920 --> 00:20:04.079
but memes, comics, TikToks, and the like serve as a really important part of content creation.

00:20:04.079 --> 00:20:08.479
And I should note, my Twitter feed is chock full of them. Just because something isn't serious

00:20:08.479 --> 00:20:14.079
doesn't mean it doesn't have educational value or importance as content. I'm thinking specifically

00:20:14.079 --> 00:20:18.880
of the wonderful zines that Julie Evans puts out that include things like learning Linux and Git.

00:20:19.439 --> 00:20:24.400
But in a fun way. You don't have to create an entire zine. Even a fun meme about R,

00:20:24.400 --> 00:20:29.839
statistics, or drawing like Alex and Horst are all great ways to share what you know and feel

00:20:29.839 --> 00:20:35.199
like you have some sort of control over the creative process. You can also do something

00:20:35.199 --> 00:20:40.239
like make a bot, which is what I did. If you like and have the opportunity to write code in your

00:20:40.239 --> 00:20:46.560
spare time, building a bot based off of an API is a fun way to learn about how the web works

00:20:47.119 --> 00:20:52.239
and cleaning your little piece of it. A few years ago, I built something called Soviet ArtBot,

00:20:52.239 --> 00:20:57.599
which as it says on the tin, scrapes wiki art for socialist realist images and tweets them out once

00:20:57.599 --> 00:21:03.119
a day. I learned a lot during this process, but what I love about it is that I get to control my

00:21:03.119 --> 00:21:08.800
online environment through code. I'm creating and changing what people see on their timelines.

00:21:08.800 --> 00:21:14.000
Art is something I always appreciate on my Twitter feed. And as an additional bonus,

00:21:14.000 --> 00:21:18.640
it gave me the time to learn about Twitter APIs and cloud computing paradigms.

00:21:20.079 --> 00:21:26.079
The three things that I just talked about are very tangible ways, but there's also very

00:21:26.079 --> 00:21:33.760
intangible ways to do so. The first one is sending an email appreciation, either an email or a note

00:21:33.760 --> 00:21:39.599
on GitHub or a comment on someone's blog. It can be to the author of your favorite art package,

00:21:39.599 --> 00:21:44.319
someone you're working with, or just someone you've seen do cool stuff online. People love

00:21:44.319 --> 00:21:49.199
getting appreciation, and in an increasingly negative and polarized world, that kind of

00:21:49.199 --> 00:21:53.760
feedback is really hard to come by. You might even get into a conversation with the author

00:21:53.760 --> 00:21:58.479
about something and create something together, which has happened to me before. What I love

00:21:58.479 --> 00:22:02.880
about this, especially with the email aspect, is that it's private, but it's still a way to

00:22:02.880 --> 00:22:09.280
send out really great positive energy out in the world. And finally, start your own community.

00:22:10.000 --> 00:22:14.239
One of the reasons that we feel overwhelmed is that big communities are intimidating.

00:22:14.800 --> 00:22:19.920
I've often talked about this theory I have called good things don't scale, where one of the reasons

00:22:19.920 --> 00:22:24.959
we get stressed out about social media is that humans are not meant to carry out as many

00:22:24.959 --> 00:22:31.199
relationships as are in Dunbar's number, 150 people. We simply can't hold it in our heads,

00:22:31.199 --> 00:22:36.880
and so lose context with all the conversations we have. The best way to fight that noise is to

00:22:36.880 --> 00:22:42.560
create a small community that can, again, be in any medium, as long as it's a medium that you

00:22:42.560 --> 00:22:47.199
and the other people in the community keep up with. For example, if you know you hate text messages,

00:22:47.199 --> 00:22:54.319
use Signal or WhatsApp. The ideal community for this is under 10, 15 people, and these people

00:22:54.319 --> 00:23:00.479
should be fairly active. A community of like-minded people who support each other is the key to

00:23:00.479 --> 00:23:06.079
fighting the bigness and the noise of the internet, because the process for caring for a garden is an

00:23:06.079 --> 00:23:13.599
important one, and it's a long-standing process, and it's made up of very large, broad range of

00:23:13.599 --> 00:23:18.959
multiple things. Every time you create something positive, you're doing a small amount of work

00:23:18.959 --> 00:23:24.079
outshining all of the negative work in the world in the internet today. You're taking away one piece

00:23:24.079 --> 00:23:30.239
of noise, one ping from your life. There are many reasons to do it, including the ones I talked about

00:23:30.239 --> 00:23:35.119
at the beginning of the talk, but mostly, for me personally, it's a wonderful way to manage my own

00:23:35.119 --> 00:23:40.959
2020 anxiety and change the world bird by bird, because when you're tending to a garden, a thistle

00:23:40.959 --> 00:23:46.400
cannot grow in that place, as Frances Hogson Burnett writes, and maybe that's just as much of a reason

00:23:46.400 --> 00:23:54.000
to create a garden as any other. It's my hope that Radio 2021 is going to be tuned to a much, much

00:23:54.000 --> 00:24:02.640
better frequency than Radio 2020. Thank you so much for your time, and I hope to see your digital gardens soon.

